<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<appendix xml:id="ap-intervals" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Intervals</title>

  <section xml:id="sec-intervals">
    <title>Intervals</title>

    <p>
      An <term>interval</term> <idx><h>interval</h> </idx> is a subset of
      <m>\R</m> of one of the following forms, where
      <m>a,b \in \R</m> and <m>a \le b</m>:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><m>(a,b):=\{x\in\R \colon a\lt x\lt b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>[a,b]:=\{x\in\R \colon a\le x\le b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>(a,b]:=\{x\in\R \colon a\lt x\le b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>[a,b):=\{x\in\R \colon a\le x\lt b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>(a,\infty):=\{x\in\R \colon a\lt x\}</m></li>
      <li><m>[a,\infty):=\{x\in\R \colon a\le x\}</m></li>
      <li><m>(-\infty,b):=\{x\in\R \colon x\lt b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>(-\infty,b]:=\{x\in\R \colon x\le b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>\R=(-\infty,\infty)</m></li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      When <m>a=b</m>, the interval <m>(a,b)</m> is the empty set and <m>[a,b]
      = \{a\}</m>. A <term>nondegenerate interval</term> is an interval with
      at least two points.
    </p>
    <p>
      An interval <m>I</m> contains every point between any two of its
      elements. In other words, <m>[x,y] \subseteq I</m> whenever <m>x,y \in
      I</m> with <m>x \le y</m>. Conversely, any subset of <m>\R</m> with
      this property is an interval.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-classification-of-intervals">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every interval in <m>\R</m> is one of the nine forms listed above.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>I \subseteq \R</m> be an interval. If <m>I=\emptyset</m>,
          then <m>I=(0,0)</m>. If <m>I=\{a\}</m> is a singleton, then
          <m>I=[a,a]</m>. So we may assume that <m>I</m> is nondegenerate.
        </p>
        <p>
          First suppose that <m>I</m> is bounded below but not bounded above.
          Let <m>a=\inf I</m>. If <m>z&gt;a</m>, then <m>z</m> is not a lower
          bound of <m>I</m>, so there is <m>x \in I</m> with <m>x&lt;z</m>.
          Since <m>I</m> is not bounded above, there is also <m>y \in I</m>
          with <m>z&lt;y</m>. Because <m>I</m> is an interval and
          <m>x&lt;z&lt;y</m>, we get <m>z \in I</m>. Thus
          <m>(a,\infty)\subseteq I</m>. On the other hand, no element of
          <m>I</m> can be less than <m>a</m>. Hence <m>I=(a,\infty)</m> or
          <m>I=[a,\infty)</m>, according as <m>a \notin I</m> or
          <m>a \in I</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The case when <m>I</m> is bounded above but not bounded below is
          similar: if <m>b=\sup I</m>, then
          <m>I=(-\infty,b)</m> or <m>I=(-\infty,b]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>I</m> is neither bounded below nor bounded above, then for
          every <m>z \in \R</m> we can choose <m>x,y \in I</m> with
          <m>x&lt;z&lt;y</m>. Hence <m>z \in I</m>, so <m>I=\R</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Finally, suppose that <m>I</m> is bounded below and above. Let
          <m>a=\inf I</m> and <m>b=\sup I</m>. Since <m>I</m> is nondegenerate,
          we have <m>a&lt;b</m>. If <m>a&lt;z&lt;b</m>, then <m>z</m> is neither
          a lower bound nor an upper bound of <m>I</m>. So there exist
          <m>x,y \in I</m> with <m>x&lt;z&lt;y</m>. Therefore <m>z \in I</m>.
          Thus <m>(a,b)\subseteq I</m>. Also every element of <m>I</m> lies in
          <m>[a,b]</m>. Consequently, <m>I</m> is one of
          <m>(a,b), [a,b], (a,b], [a,b)</m>, according to whether
          <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> belong to <m>I</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-interval-cardinality-r">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every nondegenerate interval <m>I\subseteq\R</m> has cardinality
          <m>|\R|</m>. In particular, it is uncountable.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Every such interval <m>I</m> contains an open interval
          <m>(a,b)</m> and is a subset of <m>\R</m>.  It is enough to
          show <m>|(a,b)|=|\R|</m>.  The map <m>x\mapsto (x-c)/r</m>
          with <m>c=(a+b)/2</m>, <m>r=(b-a)/2</m>, is a bijection
          <m>(a,b)\to(-1,1)</m>.  Also <m>t\mapsto\tan(\pi t/2)</m> is
          a bijection <m>(-1,1)\to\R</m>.  Hence <m>|(a,b)|=|\R|</m>,
          so <m>|I|=|\R|</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-intersection-intervals">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The intersection of two intervals is an interval.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p> Let <m>I,J</m> be intervals. Since <m>\emptyset</m> and singletons
        are intervals, we may assume <m>I \cap J</m> has at least two points
        <m>x&lt;y</m>. Since <m>I</m> and <m>J</m> are intervals, <m>[x,y]</m>
        is a subset of both <m>I</m> and <m>J</m>, and hence of <m>I\cap J</m>.
        Thus, <m>I\cap J</m> is an interval.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-union-overlapping-intervals">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The union of two overlapping intervals is an interval.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>I,J</m> be two overlapping intervals, and pick <m>a \in I
          \cap J</m>. If <m>I \cup J</m> is a singleton, then we are done.
          Otherwise, we can take <m>x \lt y</m> in <m>I \cup J</m>. We must
          show <m>[x,y] \subseteq I \cup J</m>. If both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>
          lie in the same interval, then <m>[x,y]</m> is a subset of that
          interval, hence of <m>I \cup J</m>. Otherwise, after relabeling
          we may assume <m>x \in I \setminus J</m> and <m>y \in J \setminus
          I</m>. If <m>a \lt x</m>, then <m>x \in [a,y] \subseteq J</m>,
          a contradiction. If <m>y \lt a</m>, then <m>y \in [x,a] \subseteq
          I</m>, a contradiction. Therefore <m>x \le a \le y</m>. Then we
          have <m>[x,a] \subseteq I</m> and <m>[a,y] \subseteq J</m>. Hence
          <m>[x,y]=[x,a]\cup[a,y]\subseteq I\cup J</m>, so <m>I\cup J</m>
          is an interval.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </section>

</appendix>
